abstracts.cdata!:
The Second Port Project in Spain was
            created to help major ports to meet the demands of traffic
            and to consolidate and reinforce institutional and
            organizational reforms introduced during the First Port
            Project. Upon implementation, the project ran into
            difficulties that led to completion delays, overrun of costs
            and content changes. The start of the project was delayed
            two years, which resulted in a twenty-three percent increase
            in the initial cost. Some setbacks and difficulties
            encountered during the project were due to lack of
            preparation. The project was part of a long-term plan to
            expand Spain's port capacity.  Despite setbacks, the
            main goals of the project were achieved.
